// examples/esp32/minimal.kr — the smallest --target=esp32 program, used by
// tests/run_tests.sh `esp32_image_structure` to inspect the esp-image the
// compiler emits (design doc §1/§3: two RAM segments the ESP32 mask ROM
// loads directly from flash offset 0x1000).
//
// Build:
//   krc --arch=xtensa --freestanding --target=esp32 \
//       examples/esp32/minimal.kr -o minimal.bin
//
// Expected image shape (asserted by the structure test with od only):
//   segment 0 = DRAM data @ 0x3FFB0000   (strings + statics — byte-addressable)
//   segment 1 = IRAM code @ 0x40080400   (code + literal pools ONLY)
//   entry inside [0x40080400, 0x400A0000)
//
// The one INITIALIZED static below is deliberate, not decoration: esptool
// omits empty sections, so the compiler skips zero-length segments to stay
// byte-comparable with `elf2image` output. A truly empty program would
// legitimately produce a 1-segment image; `marker = 42` keeps the DRAM
// segment non-empty so the 2-segment assertion holds.

static u32 marker = 42

fn main() {
    marker = marker + 1     // STATIC_LOAD/STORE — a real DRAM data reference
    // Freestanding: nothing to return to. Park the core forever.
    loop { }
}
